Basic Visualization and Linear Regression

Letâs start by looking at the data. The geom_point function will help us plot simple points in the data. I want to look at MPG and weight:

mtcars %>%
   ggplot() +
   geom_point(aes(x = wt, y = mpg)) +
   labs(x = "Weight", y = "Miles Per Gallon", title = "MPG by Weight")

It seems like there is a relationship here. Letâs use linear regression to analyze it.

mpg_on_weight <- mtcars %>% lm(mpg ~ wt, data = .)
mpg_on_weight

Now that we have a model in hand, letâs visualize it. I have outlined three different ways below:

  • Method 1
  • Method 2
  • Method 3

First, letâs take the original dataset, tack the fitted values from the model onto it, and call it something new:

cars_df <- mtcars %>% mutate(fitted = mpg_on_weight$fitted.values)

Now, letâs pipe this new data frame into a ggplot call with geom_line

cars_df %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = wt, y = mpg)) +
   geom_point() +
   geom_line(aes(y = fitted), col = "red")

In this example, we take the coefficients directly from the model. Note that this is not very tidy of us1

mtcars %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = wt, y = mpg)) +
   geom_point() +
   geom_abline(
      intercept = mpg_on_weight$coefficients[1],
      slope = mpg_on_weight$coefficients[2],
      col = "red")

If all we care about is visualization (rather than actual data values), we can use geom_smooth:

mtcars %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = wt, y = mpg)) +
   geom_point() +
   geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, col ="red")

We can even visualize confidence intervals by leaving out se = F. Iâll leave this for you to do.

Caution

Note the error produced here:

mtcars %>%
   ggplot() +
   geom_point(aes(x = wt, y = mpg)) +
   geom_smooth(method = "lm")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
Error in `geom_smooth()`:
! Problem while computing stat.
â¹ Error occurred in the 2nd layer.
Caused by error in `compute_layer()`:
! `stat_smooth()` requires the following missing aesthetics: x and y

We specified the aesthetic mapping (aes) at the geom_ level. When looking for aesthetics, geoms look for an aes mapping in the ggplot() level, but does not look elsewhere.

Therefore, we have to specify the mapping at the ggplot level, or give another aesthetic mapping (aes) call to geom_smooth

Further Analysis

Facets Example

For the sake of exposure, hereâs an example thatâs a little extra:

Code 
mtcars %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = wt, y = mpg)) +
   geom_point() +
   geom_smooth(aes(col=as.factor(am)), method = 'lm', se = F) +
   facet_wrap(~am, scales = "free_x",
      labeller = labeller(
         am = c("0" = "Auto",
                "1" = "Manual")
      ) #for this call specficially, my indentation is non-standard 
   ) +
   scale_color_manual(
      name = "Automatic vs. Maunal", 
      values = c("red", "blue"),
      labels = c("Auto", "Man")
   ) +
   labs(
      title = "Effect of weight on MPG, by Transmission",
      x = "Weight (1000s lbs.)",
      y = "Miles Per Gallon"
   ) +
   theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Colors in and out of aes

Compare the following code blocks and their respective outputs:

  • Inside AES
  • Outside AES
mtcars %>%
   ggplot() +
   geom_point(aes(x = wt, y = mpg, col = as.factor(cyl)))

mtcars %>%
   ggplot() +
   geom_point(aes(x = wt, y = mpg), col = mtcars$cyl)

  • What I donât want you to worry about is the color scale and the as.factor call

  • What I do want you to notice:

    • Outside AES, geom_point doesnât know what cyl is

      • Therefore, we have to call mtcars again2

    • Outside AES, we donât have a legend key

      • There is actually more to this than it may seem

Inside/Outside AES, Explained

  • Crucially, when you put something in âaesâ, it maps your varaible to a built-in âaestheticâ that ggplot knows.

  • So, you can think of the colors, shapes, sizes, etc. inside aes() as their own layers/characteristics of the plot

  • On the other hand, colors (etc.) outside aes can be thought of as low-level options that we told a geom to use

  • This may seem minor right now. When you are on your own, make sure you are aware of whether things like color, size, shape, fill are inside or outside an aes() call

To do a quick-check for heteroskedasticity, we can plot the residuals

cars_df %<>% mutate(resid = lm.res) 

cars_df %>% 
   ggplot() + 
   geom_point(aes(x = wt, y = resid))

## Looks good

However, another helpful function in the tidyverse is broomâs augment() function. It takes in a model, and outputs a data frame with the data used, fitted values, residuals, and more already baked in!

Letâs Try it:

lm.mod <- mpg_on_weight %>% broom::augment()

Now, letâs visualize the residual values for each point in the data:

lm.mod %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = wt, y = mpg)) +
   geom_point() +
   geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) +
   geom_segment(aes(xend = wt, yend = .fitted), col = "red")

Since residuals are just the difference between actual and fitted values, we could also do

lm.mod %>%
   ggplot(aes(x = wt, y = mpg)) +
   geom_point() +
   geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) +
   geom_segment(aes(xend = wt, yend = mpg - .resid), col = "darkgreen")
